After a few modifications to make it printer-friendly, the hydra lives!
Use this Hydra figurine, depicting the mythical multi-headed beast bickering among itself, to make any space more lively.  Set it up in the kitchen as a decoration, in the bedroom to guard you while you sleep, or hide it in a rival's locker to scare the Hades out of them.

Print the sculpture using full support (raft recommended), clean, and enjoy!

description.text:
1.25 pound fractional weight plates are used in linear progression weightlifting routines like Greyskull LP.

Most weight sets have a lowest weight plate of 2.5 pounds, which only allows for 5 pound progressions. 1.25 plates allow for 2.5 pound progressions which can be better for upper body exercises like the overhead and bench press or barbell rows.

1.25 pound plates are, however, disproportionately expensive to purchase. Included here is a shell which you can fill with sand, or as I did, pennies, to print and create your own fractional plates.

These plates fit a standard 2-inch Olympic barbell.

STEPS

  1. For each weight plate, print two shells and a plug
  2. Fill one of the shells with about 175 pennies or about 1.25 cups of sand, total weight of the two shells, plug and filling should be 20 ounces (567 grams)
  3. Glue the second shell on to the first
  4. Stuff cotton, rags or paper into the fill hole to fill the space not occupied by pennies, remove pennies if the stuffing puts your weight over 20 ounces
  5. Insert the plug into the fill hole, it should not be necessary to glue it

description.text:
This is my CR10-S4/S5 2020 Nema MOTOR MOUNT STIFFENER V1 The Purpose of this mod is to stiffen/support the stock Y AXIS NEMA MOTOR MOUNT, and aswell Elimate most if not all of the vibrations caused by the flimsy stock/cheap mount. This is an extremely tight fit. this is what i wanted, and for sure you dont any gap between Nema and mount, also once it gets over the front silver section(motor face) of the NEMA which is slightly thicker it will be smoother towards the black middle section which measures 42.3mm. Put some elbow grease into it youll be fine!!, and if you cant do it lol then actually use a tab bit of grease to get over the beginings slight rise. :) GL, HF, and Happy Printing!!!

-Parts Needed:

-4X M4 Stainless Steel Button Head Hex Socket Cap Screws Bolts.
-4X M4 2020 Drop In Post Assembly T-nut.

***NOTE:

-THERE ARE DIFFERENT VERSIONS OF THE S4 NEMA MOTOR MOUNT DEPENDING ON YOURS THIS MAY NOT FIT!!

-When using the M4 bolts, make sure to drop 1 T-Nut in 2020, and then align with M4 screw and tighten. If you are having trouble aligning the t-nut use this method.

-Remember mount will be tight man strength is needed a little, the hole like the 2nd pic above has to be inserted into the CR10 stock metal mount, the mount goes toward the rear of the nema resting on the connector. The stiffner mount walls measure at 4mm. they are not supposed to line up lol, why? well because i wanted them thicker than 2mm

description.text:
I haven's seen a similar toy around so I started a Fusion 360 practice project.
This roller is inspired by Bomag machine which was on duty in our street while road renovation took place.

Print Rite DIY

No

Yes

20 %

Printed in PLA.
I recommend 3 or 4 perimeters for strength and 3 or 4 top/bottom solid layers.
I printed from the side because I think is the best way for making holes for axle holders fit properly. I prepared files also for being printed regularly. If you print the roller from the side you will need to attach LEGO knobs after, because knobs can't be printed sideways.

description.text:
Looking for another model to feature my super-cool rotary engraved tires I came across the classic Mercedes Benz Unimog. The multi-purpose 4x4 truck was developed in 1945 and the 406-series started 1963. The name is an abbreviation of Universal-Motor-Gerät.

My build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute. I used 6.5 mm beech plywood and 20 mm acacia wood for the tires. The tires were engraved by my poor man's 4th axis. Two 6 mm beech rod made the axles, nylon spacers provide a low friction.

A laser cutter might be a good alternative tool to create smaller versions, you just need to find a solution for the engraved tires.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/Toys/Cars for more toy cars designs.

Keep in mind, that the stl is for three dimensional viewing purpose only. It will not print well on a fdm printer!

description.text:
This a 3D printed Zeotrope fidget spinner. As the wheel spins, the images placed inside the wheel make a small movie. Animations are hand cut and placed, as individual frames, but there is probably a simpler way to make animations swappable.

The original design is found on Instructables, but it did not work well as it was submitted there. The main modifications I made are to the caps, so they stay in place, the original ones did not stay in place, and no mechanism for an effective fit to the bearing. The other modifications were to remove the 3D lettering on the hubs and the wheel. The lettering went completely through the wheel, which was not appealing.

Full credit is given to the original designer on Instructables.

Printer:

Monoprice 3D Select Mini

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

50

Notes:

Print 1x: wheel
Print 2x: hub, cap v2, Zeotrope cap v2

Print cap v2 standing on the small end, with brim and supports, it will turn out much better that way.

Print hub with flat side to the bottom of the build plate, there will be no overhangs that way.

Print Zeotrope cap v2 standing on the base. I did not need a brim, but if you do not get good adhesion, you might use one.

For bearings use standard skateboard bearings 22mm outer diameter, 8mm inner diameter, 7mm height. For standard 7 ball bearings, remove the dust shield, take apart the bearing and remove 3 balls. Reassemble, minus the dust shield, it is unnecessary and causes more friction.

I cut each individual frame and applied them with double sided tape to the inside of the wheel.

description.text:
This is about the smallest inline endstop I could come up with for the Y rail. I needed the limit switch below the Y-carriage for another project I am working on. it's angled to line up with the Y belt anchor bracket for either the trinitylabs or makerstoolworks Y rails, but should also work on other projects.   
As there really isn't much plastic for your anchor bolts to bite into for the  Y switch mount itself, you will need some washers.   
Right and left versions included, for use on either side of the rail.

print it with support. I found end printing was easiest. then trim the keyway notch to fit your rail and screw it down. The Y switch is held on by bolts threaded into the plastic itself. seems to be holding up fine so far, though I may try for a nut backed one later.

description.text: ashtray real madrid

Originally designed with Tinkercad, this plane is quick and easy to print and with minimal assembly (all that is required is some kind of tape or glue to attach wings and propellor)! All the parts are in one file for easy access, and the print time is less than an hour (on most printers).

Assembly

The simple assembly only has 5 steps.

  1. Attach the front plane face (the disc) to the fuselage (the cone). All of the steps including this one require the tape or glue, although hot or gorilla glue is recommended.

  2. Attach the propeller (the bowtie-looking object) to the front of the plane. Sadly it does not spin without modifications, and I may try to make an MK-2 of this with a spinning propellor.

  3. Attach the large set of wings to the flat part of the fuselage (on top) and wait until glue is dry. Make sure the wings are centered or angled to your desire.

  4. Attach the small set of wings to the back of the fuselage (near the tip, but still on the same side as the other wings).

  5. Attach the tail fin perpendicular and over the middle of the small wings to create an "upside-down T shape".

Your plane is now finished, so fly away with your imagination!

description.text: I was curious how various image textures would work as displacement maps so I mapped them on the faces of a cube gear cube. These cubes aren't ideal for mapping all photos because there's an enormous gap right in the center of each face, but for textures they look pretty good.

You'll need 8 pins and the pin STL only has 2, so print that 4 times. I had some problems printing out a whole plate of these all at once so this was more convenient for me.

This was made with approximately the same procedure I used for the Hellraiser Cube Gears, with a few adjustments:

  1. When assigning the vertices for each vertex group, leave a margin around each side. I found it was easiest to subdivide the cube into small blocks, but not too small. Then you can select all the vertices on a side and use the Select->SelectLess function several times to shrink it back from the edges. You can then subdivide your side patch as much as you want, before assigning it to a group. This was necessary even though I had manually added a white border around each texture.
  2. For some reason my textured cube was still causing the PLA Gear Kit to emit assertion violations, which only stopped after I went back to my Blender model and decimated the geometry to about 80%. I'm not sure what that changed, but it certainly didn't hurt anything.

description.text:
I found an Kodak Instamatic X-25 at a thrift shop for 3$, but no film. After consulting Dr. Google the end result is that the film is very expensive and very hard to duplicate due to the unique cartridge that comes with it- but there has been next to no progress on making a 3D print of that.

So, in lieu of making one of those I made this, it's a coupler for any regular 35mm film to the inside of the Instamatic, allowing for it to take regular film. The only catch is that you have to saw or grind down the top of the film reel so that it will fit, and the other is that this part historically will break on me once the film is completely advanced- which is why I included the print as a set of 3 and wouldn't consider gluing any parts in place.

The flat end with four indentations connects with the inside of the gear of the camera, while the two spokes connect with the film. To use, first get a regular 35mm take up spool for it to wrap around, and tightly wind your film on that. Then using the coupler connect your film roll to the camera. Close the system and be sure to use black-out tape or some other equivalent for the back window originally supposed to be for the number of photos left.

title: Yuneec Q500 Parts Storage Box, Battery Sized.

description.text:
I have an after-market case for my Q500 which has slots for all the accessories, but nothing for the extra little stuff like filters, SD cards, etc. I have extra battery slots, but they are too deep to fish little things out of. I decided to make a battery shaped box to hold all those extra parts.

Infill level probably doesn't matter since the walls aren't thick enough to use much. I printed it fairly solid knowing I was going to be stuffing it in and out of a tight foam slot. I used clear packing tape for a hinge, so I wouldn't lose the top, but you don't have to. It fits tightly when closed.

To give fair credit, I took the idea of a battery shaped case from a video Adam Savage (YouTube "Tested" Channel) did on his new DJI Inspire years ago.

Notes:

Printed in cheap PLA at 198 C with printer bed at 45 C. Skirting was used to help prime the heads before actual print was started

Paint job

The bottom plate will need to be glued into place to complete the cube body.

I am not a model maker so all I did was to spray paint this black ( may not be needed if printed in black filament first) then lightly sprayed with gold paint.

Fusion 360

I had seen another version of this on the web and while I commend the person responsible for making the cube, I had issues with it. It wasn't symmetrical nor was is completely square and the top would not fit if rotated 90 degrees. Also the etching on the cube sides was not consistent from side to side which really set my into an OCD fit (and I don't suffer from OCD). It took me a while to get what little information I could gather to try and best replicate the actual cube design. Big shout outs to my friend Adam for creating the sigil on the top lid piece.

I made this using Fusion 360 in 3 parts to try and eliminate any unwanted or wasted filament on supports. I did not use any supports on this when I printed this and set my slicer to print external shells last. I use IdeaMaker for my slicer and slowed my first layer down to 10 mm/s to ensure good adhesion on my printer bed.

I used the cheapest green filament I had and a .3 mm nozzle with .2 mm layer height and a .2 mm first layer height. After the first layer I print at 40 mm/s (your printer may do fine at faster/slower speeds).

Open to questions & Comments

Please tell me what you think or if you have any questions or other comments on this project. I am not a 3d designer and do the best I can with what little skills I have taught myself over the last several months. I am always open to more experienced 3d designers giving me an encouraging word, word of advice or even polite criticism.
